@ 22 July
Lille Richle Shuthell
Sr. the 15:th curitt remitted you the £50:0- on John packett which I hope is
well come to yd handes thought sence non from you so shall further answer
yd of 16: curitt do still hope that yd naturalisation shall pass according
tolaer, that you shall finde yd bussynss & trade to content I have
give you creditt for my share in the bale N.10 & what further you de
shall be approved of, for I referre all to yd prudent menagement, here
all things go vere slowley, no, or a small sale, & hadely, many to be had
for goods sold yett those that sett up here besune mighty brishe
&HM is their finde, he wrott mee pr. formar post to see mee in the
winter next, this day receaved a letter from him where in he tell
mee to be here vere sudd amlij to speake to a freind butt not concerning
wollen manifactoryes, so they are all for advancing their owne inrest
& rinning the trade as mr. randall doth much for he serves many of
our shop keepers thing they waat 3 o14 sorts to make up one bale by
that wee dayly appressend warr: the more sence the freinch king is so
much upon us, intrim the Engliss are asleep, & quarrell about the
plott, butt I supose the plost will come to anend, sence my lore
shofs burry the cheaf in ventor is a close prissncor precy a word
of advise of what passes whilst premen
In Antwerp 23 July 1
London Lucy knightley
th 2
Sr. in answer to yd of 8: curitt. as to what you draw on my acctt. is alwayes hindely
accepted & punctually payd, & thought to yd & my freinds accommodation, you have
beeu pressed some thimes there unto, yett itt hath been no less honoured, butt
I supose he will now desist there in, because his intrest here declines vre much
& Iendeavour to avoid all manner of drawing & redrawing where fore hope
to sell off his resting goods & make an end so itt t: observe what you write
concerning the 6N. I hope you shall prevaile with the maker to deliver you the
5 p. pr vere first & if I could butt gett in here with our father Jesuitts o deliver
them I should be able to advise you how mony peeces I should receauw yearly
where fore crustly wish to have the 5p. for atryall & that the sooner & the
better of which shall be gladd to have the news of the succes: steven warnier
with the last bale of reds is well arrived & the goods are on their way from
bruges. hether I can not yett utt off yd kerseds itt beeng asort not much
uso here & much in knowne, yett shall endeavour to sell y as best I can p7d
next please to note the first cost & charges of them whilst I remaine
London Henry Maynard
th
23 ditto 1681
Sr. my last to you was on the 19: curitt to which please to be referred sence rect
yd of 8 ditto bij which I understand yd resolution to leave london for 10 a 12 dayds
you will be keartely wel kom, here & then wee may diecours further so shall not
cen large, onely that I have given credies for my half share in the bale N. 33, the
patt. are in different: well assorted & where as I want more spanish cloathes
of all sorts, butt most low prijses, so should wish you would pick up now
& then a good cloth, att leest for half drap cullours of a lively please cullour
the rest as best you can iudge because I do not know my self which to invede
I have seen a pattarne boock for 24 cloathes in 2 bales which you sent to JK
of brussels & itt may be not yett come to his handes amoughst them were
severall lovely cullours, so you knowing the demanded sorts will do well to provide
& ouy some when you most meet them to content though itt ware to make every
12 dayes a 3 weeks one bale, each bale to be vrapped with 2 bayes onely or
Rather a demy cottong till you can send mee bayes from london that are
worth the 45:6 a 44 st those I receave from the north of 36 a 37 are mn
better please further to buy one pach of white cottons besides that in ordered
forredI vit from 22 to 25 pence a goad 12 demy cottons m abale & ½ for vrapped
& send them with first opportaniie seeng the 6N silver stuck cloathes
can not be sooner ready imust have posentie & stay out the time wee have no
news yett of Richd pindar I could wish the goods here whist I remaine
@ 23 ditto 87
London Abram vivian
th
S. my last to you was on the 19 curitt sence recd. yd of 8 ditto tis well you wa
shall given the nessecary order to provide the desired bale of fine long cloather
I long to know how our goods are shipped & so much want the kersies here
I leave the whole divection on yd side to yd self all I have to say that is
that I may have good goods & punctuall provided that no noglect be comitted
in dispatch: I supose for the future mr. potter must be the man, as also in bayes
for mr. Chipping comitts great fault & never yett had ond pes. sort weres
now there comes 2 sorts never, should any bayes be packt butt that before
they must be assorted, & each bale with itts korts perticular mentioned
in the invoyce as mr. schipping didother wise itt is a
confusion to mee here if m. chipping be not satisfied that 2 bayes are to
little I can send acert ficatie signed by 2 that I have iu ployd to the purpose
to open all 3 the bales togheter. yd bill of £200: shall accept & passto
yd acctt. and shall be mightly gladd to see you here where fore as soone
as you thingk couveient, you can comebutt our goods ought most part
to be dispatched which I do supose will vere well be 3 freekes hence of
what further passes exspect tijds advise I remanne
